CONCLUSION  
  
This assignment taught me that building AI agents is about designing good systems, not just 
writing prompts. The 4-layer architecture provides a reusable framework that makes 
debugging and improvement much easier. 
 
The hardest part was maintaining context without persistent memory, but solving this taught 
me creative prompt engineering. The most enjoyable part was the iterative refinement—
watching each prompt adjustment improve the agent's consistency and reliability. 
 
I learned that effective prompts require specificity and structure. My first attempt was too 
vague. Adding concrete examples, clear decision logic, and output templates made the 
agent significantly better. When stuck, I analyzed specific failures and provided clearer 
criteria. 
 
As someone seeking an ML/AI internship, this exercise forced me to think like a product 
engineer—considering UX, edge cases, and scalability. I learned that well-designed prompt 
architecture matters more than clever wording. 
 
With more time, I'd add persistent storage, code execution, analytics, company-specific 
questions, spaced repetition, a web interface, and voice interaction—transforming this into a 
production-ready platform. 
 
This isn't just an assignment—it's a tool I'll use and improve during my internship search. 
